{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5144022c-b85a-4158-87d5-ba32f4f01ad2","content":"With MSTest 3.8.2, you can use **constructor injection** for `TestContext` and implement `IAsyncInitialization` for async setup. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    // Synchronous initialization via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here (e.g., create objects, set defaults)\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous initialization\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup here (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor** — receives `TestContext` via DI; use for sync setup.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — implement `InitializeAsync()` for async work that runs before each test.\n- This replaces the older `[TestInitialize]` / property-setter pattern while keeping both sync and async paths clean.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"afad8666-662f-4a78-9191-5e77e8eac9ff","outputTokens":296,"requestId":"581C:3DF1E0:16EFCBB:18662BA:6A0338AA"},"id":"8274db22-c348-445e-a7fa-b0bac552834c","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:26:57.507Z","parentId":"3dd64673-7555-4000-a0b2-9ed931993aaf"}
